Chronic conditions and logistic regression

Matthew Rudd

2/10/2022

The 2009 NAMCS and chronic conditions

The null model

chronic.null <- mean( chronic$Condition) 

chronic %>% 
  group_by(Condition)  %>% 
  summarize( N=n(), Percentage = N/nrow(chronic))

A useless plot

ggplot( chronic, aes(Age, Condition)) + geom_point()

Some useful plots

cohorts <- chronic %>% 
  group_by(Age) %>% 
  summarize( N=n(), Percentage = sum(Condition)/N )

ggplot( cohorts, aes(Age, Percentage)) + geom_point() + ylim(0,1)

chronic <- chronic %>%
  mutate( Decade = 10*round(Age/10))

decades <- chronic %>%
  group_by( Decade ) %>%
  summarize( N=n(), Percentage = sum(Condition)/N )

# using knitr's kable function :
# knitr::kable( decades )

# using pander :
# pander( decades )

# using flextable's regulartable function :
regulartable( decades ) %>% autofit()
ggplot( cohorts, aes(Age, Percentage)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_point( data=decades, aes(Decade, Percentage), color="tomato", size=3) + 
  ylim(0,1)

The curve of chance

z <- seq(-5, 5, len=1000)
logistic <- data.frame( z=z, sigma = 1 / (1 + exp(-z)))
ggplot( logistic, aes(z,sigma)) + 
  geom_line( size=1 ) +
  labs( title = "The logistic curve")

This is a plot of the logistic curve a.k.a. the logistic function a.k.a. the sigmoid function

\[ \sigma( z ) ~ = ~ \frac{ 1 }{ 1 + e^{-z}} \ . \]

Fitting the logistic curve to our data

chronic.fit <- glm( Condition ~ Age, data=chronic, family="binomial")
chronic.fit 
## 
## Call:  glm(formula = Condition ~ Age, family = "binomial", data = chronic)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)          Age  
##    -2.03938      0.05182  
## 
## Degrees of Freedom: 31432 Total (i.e. Null);  31431 Residual
## Null Deviance:       42830 
## Residual Deviance: 33840     AIC: 33840

The fitted logistic regression model is therefore

\[ \text{Probability of condition} ~ = ~ \sigma( -2.03938 + 0.05182 \times \text{Age}) \ . \]

To phrase this in terms of the odds of having a condition, recall the definition of the odds of something happening:

\[ \text{Odds of event} ~ = ~ \frac{ \text{Probability of event} }{ 1 - \text{Probability of event} } \ . \] In terms of odds, our logistic model is

\[ \log{ ( \text{Odds of a condition} ) } ~ = ~ -2.03938 + 0.05182 \times \text{Age} \ . \]

The odds ratio

One way to summarize this model is to report its odds ratio, which is the logistic regression analogue of the slope in linear regression. To derive the expression for the odds ratio, we first need to solve the equation

\[ y ~ = ~ \sigma(z) ~ = ~ \frac{ 1 }{ 1 + e^{-z}} \] for \(z\) ; doing the necessary manipulation yields

\[ z ~ = ~ \log{ \left( \frac{ y }{ 1 - y } \right) } \ . \]

This inverse function of the logistic function is known as the logit : by definition,

\[ \operatorname{logit}( y ) ~ = ~ \log{ \left( \frac{ y }{ 1 - y } \right) } \ . \]

Putting this all together, a simple logistic model with predictor variable \(x\) has two equivalent forms:

\[ \text{Probability of event} = \sigma( a + bx ) \quad \iff \quad \log{(\text{Odds of event})} = a + bx \ . \]

Exponentiating the second form yields yet another formulation:

\[ \text{Odds of event} ~ = ~ e^{a+bx} ~ = ~ e^{a} e^{bx} \ . \] Now we get to the odds ratio. Fix a value \(x_{0}\) of the predictor and compare the odds when \(x=x_{0}\) to the odds when \(x=x_{0}+1\):

\[ \text{Odds when} \left\{ x=x_{0}+1 \right\} ~ = ~ e^{a} e^{bx_{0}} e^{b} ~ = ~ e^{b} \times \text{Odds when} \left\{ x=x_{0} \right\} \ . \]

The odds get multiplied by the factor \(e^{b}\), which is, by definition, the model’s odds ratio.

The odds ratio tells us how the odds change when the predictor increases by 1 unit: multiply the odds by the odds ratio.

For the logistic chronic condition model:

chronic.or <- exp( chronic.fit$coefficients[2] )
chronic.or
##      Age 
## 1.053181

The odds ratio is 1.053181, so the odds of having a chronic condition increase by about 5% with each 1 year increase in Age. A 10-year increase in Age therefore leads to a multiplier of

chronic.or^10
##      Age 
## 1.678923

i.e., a 68% increase in the odds of having a chronic condition. A 50-year increase in Age leads to a multiplier of

chronic.or^50
##      Age 
## 13.33992

so the odds of a random 70-year-old having a chronic condition are more than 13 times the odds of a random 20-year-old having a chronic condition. Ah, the golden years after retirement!
